    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm stuck on a section of my dissertation. I've got a result where the p-value is 0.06. My advisor says it's \"not statistically significant,\" but there's a really clear trend in the visual data. Can you explain why we can't just call this a significant finding? Also, how much of this is just due to random noise in the sample?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A p-value of 0.06, while close, is generally not considered statistically significant because it exceeds the conventional alpha threshold of 0.05. This means there is a 6% chance of observing your results, even if there is truly no effect in the population. To address your concern about the trend versus noise, the p-value is a measure of the probability of the data occurring by chance, and a higher p-value suggests that randomness is a more likely explanation than a real effect. You might consider reporting this as a \"trend\" or \"marginal significance\" rather than a definitive finding.",
      "source": "target",
